Based on the search results, here's what I found about styling `input type="range"` with `::-webkit-slider-thumb` CSS and common issues:

## Key Points for Styling Range Inputs

### Essential Requirements for WebKit/Chrome:

You'll need to tell webkit you want nothing to do with their default styles by including a `-webkit-appearance: none;` on both the input and the thumb.

The basic working CSS structure is:
```css
input[type=range]{
    -webkit-appearance: none;
}

input[type=range]::-webkit-slider-thumb {
    -webkit-appearance: none;
    /* your custom styles */
}
```

### Common Issue: Grouped Selectors Don't Work

Important notice: do not group pseudo selectors with browser prefixes together. So things like `::-ms-track` & `::-webkit-slider-thumb` should be separate even if they share the same CSS rules because browsers will invalidate the pseudo selector they do not recognize and in turn invalidate the whole CSS block.(no content)You cannot link together selectors for both Firefox and Chrome - an invalid selector invalidates the entire block of properties. For example, `::-webkit-slider-thumb, ::-moz-range-thumb { background:orange; }` will not work, but separating them will work.

### Firefox Differences

In Chrome you can use `-webkit-appearance:none;` and get away with styling the element as you wish. That does not work in Firefox. For Firefox, use `::-moz-range-thumb` and `::-moz-range-track` pseudo selectors.

### UXP-Specific Notes

The search results don't specifically address Adobe UXP (Unified Extensibility Platform) issues. UXP has its own rendering engine which may not fully support all WebKit pseudo-elements. If you're working with UXP (for Adobe plugins like Photoshop/XD), you may need to check Adobe's UXP documentation for supported CSS properties, as it has limited CSS support compared to standard browsers.


